# Plot reduction in within cluster variation for each k in a series of k means cluster models...



from sklearn.datasets.samples_generator import make_blobs
X, y_true = make_blobs(n_samples=300, centers=4,
                       cluster_std=0.60, random_state=0)

within_cluster_variance = [] # initiate empty list with no data

# build models for range of ks from 2 to 20
for k in range(2, 20):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    within_cluster_variance.append(kmeans.inertia_)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.plot(range(2, 20), within_cluster_variance, marker='o')
plt.grid(True)
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Reduction in within cluster variation')

plt.title('Elbow curve')  #Choose k at elbow of plot as a general rule.  We want a small enough number of categories to 
                          # such that we can still learn something meaningful from them via exploration of our variables.
Out[77]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Elbow curve')

Describe variables that cluster with higher values of wine quality. Describe variables that cluster with lower values of wine quality.¶

If you want to make a good bottle of wine, then what characteristics are most important according to this analysis?¶

Higher qualtity wines include lower volatile acidity, higher fixed acidity, higher sulphates, higher citric acid, lower pH, and higher alcohol content.

Lower quality wines include higher sugar, higher free and total sulfer dioxide, and lower alcohol content.

If I were to make a bottle of wine off this data, I would make sure to balance the acidity by making the fixed acidity higher than average and volatile lower. I would also make sure the alcohol content is higher. I'm no wine expert, but I think that might come about by aging it. I would also make sure there are more sulfates than average. How to make this all happen? I'm not sure, I need to take a wine class :)

Describe variables that cluster with higher values of wine quality. Describe variables that cluster with lower values of wine quality.¶

If you want to make a good bottle of wine, then what characteristics are most important according to this analysis? Have your conclusions changed using Hierarchical clustering rather than k means clustering? Present any figures that assist you in your analysis.¶

The majority of observations are within one cluster, as seen in the plot above.I already don't trust this model as much, it seems to perform worse than the K Means model. I will try a different way below to see if another linkage might work better.

Cluster 1 holds the lowest quality wines (~ -1.4 ), much lower than the last model (lowest cluster ~ -.44. ). Cluster 0 is about avg quality and cluster 2 is higher quality (~ .3) but not as high as the K means model (~ .56). This is not surprising, since the one cluster is so large, so likely holds enough of the observations to have average quality.

The characterisitcs of higher quality wine in this model are lower than avg volatile acidity (-0.73), much higher residual sugar (6.54 ), higher free sulfur dioxide (1.39), higher total sulfur dioxide (1.53), and higher density.

The characterisitcs of lower quality wine in this model are higher citric acid (3.13), extremely high clorides (11.1), lower pH (-2.7), higher sulphates (5.7) and lower alcohol (~-1).

As mentioned before, I wouldn't trust this model to help me figure out how to make quality wine, so I'd use the K Means or find different arguments than previously direvted. (see below)

How much of the variation in your data is explained by the first two principal components. How might you use the first two components to do supervised learning on some other variable tied to wine (e.g. - wine price)?¶

Only a small portion of the data is explained by the first two components (.26 and .187 var ratio respectively, altogether about 45% of the data).
